xual Types demonstrates how the sodomite, the tribade (a woman-loving woman), the narcissistic courtier, the citizen wife, the bawd, and the court favorite function as sites of ideological contradiction in dramatic texts. On the one hand, these sexual types are vilified and disciplined for violating social and sexual norms; on the other hand, they can take the form of dynamic, resourceful characters who expose the limitations of the categories that attempt to define and contain them. In bringing sexuality and character studies into conjunction with one another, Sexual Types provides illuminating new readings of familiar plays, such as Shakespeare's A Midsummer Night's Dream and The Winter's Tale, and of lesser-known plays by Fletcher, Middleton, and Shirley.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCharacters and characteristics in literature. 0aEnglish dramax17th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish dramaxEarly modern and Elizabethand500-1600xHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish dramaxEarly modern and Elizabethan. 0aEnglish dramay17th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish dramayEarly modern and Elizabethan, 1500-1600xHistory and criticism. 0aSex in literature. 0aStereotypes (Social psychology) in literature. 0aTypology (Psychology) in literature. 4aLiterature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aGender Studies.  aLC.  aLiterature.  aMedieval and Renaissance Studies.  aWomen's Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook-Package Literaturez978311041354008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps:/